<section xml:id="review-radical-functions-and-equations">

    <title>Radical Functions and Equations Chapter Review</title>

    <subsection>
        <title>Introduction to Radical Functions</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-introduction-to-radical-functions">Section</xref> we covered the square root and other root functions. We learned how to find the <xref ref="fact-domain-of-radicals" text="title">domain of radical functions</xref> algebraically and the range graphically. We also saw the <xref ref="fact-distance-formula" text="title">distance formula</xref> which is an application of square roots.</p>

        <example>
            <title>The Square Root Function</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Algebraically find the domain of the function <m>f</m> where <m>f(x)=\sqrt{3x-1}+2</m> and then find the range by making a graph.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Using <xref ref="fact-domain-of-radicals">Fact</xref> to find the function's domain, we set the radicand greater than or equal to zero and solve:<md>
                    <mrow>3x-1\amp\ge0</mrow>
                    <mrow>3x\amp\ge1</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp\ge\frac{1}{3}</mrow>
                </md>The function's domain is <m>\left[\frac{1}{3},\infty\right)</m> in interval notation.</p>

                <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%">
                    <p>To find the function's range, we use technology to look at a graph of the function. The graph shows that the function's range is <m>[2,\infty)</m>. The graph also verifies the function's domain is indeed <m>\left[\frac{1}{3},\infty\right)</m>.</p>

                    <figure>
                        <caption>Graph of <m>f(x)=\sqrt{3x-1}+2</m></caption>
                        <image>
                            <description></description>
                            <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[ymin=-1,ymax=6,xmin=-1,xmax=10,
                                            ytick={0,1,...,5}, xtick={0,1,...,9}]
                                    \addplot [primarycurve, -, domain=0.333:0.34] {sqrt(3*x-1)+2};
                                    \addplot [primarycurve, -{Kite}, domain=0.34:5.667, samples=100] {sqrt(3*x-1)+2};
                                    \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(1/3,2)} node [right, color=firstcolor] {$(\frac{1}{3},2)$};
                                \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                            ]]>
                            </latex-image>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <title>The Distance Formula</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Find the distance between <m>(6,-13)</m> and <m>(-4,17)</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To calculate the distance between <m>(6,-13)</m> and <m>(-4,17)</m>, we use the distance formula. It's good practice to mark each value with the corresponding variables in the formula:<me>(\stackrel{x_1}{6},\stackrel{y_1}{-13}), (\stackrel{x_2}{-4},\stackrel{y_2}{17})</me> We have:
                <md>
                    <mrow>d\amp=\sqrt{(x_2-x_1)^2+(y_2-y_1)^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>d\amp=\sqrt{\left(\substitute{-4}-\substitute{6}\right)^2+\left(\substitute{17}-\substitute{(-13)}\right)^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>d\amp=\sqrt{\left(-10\right)^2+\left(30\right)^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>d\amp=\sqrt{100+900}</mrow>
                    <mrow>d\amp=\sqrt{1000}</mrow>
                    <mrow>d\amp=\sqrt{100}\cdot\sqrt{10}</mrow>
                    <mrow>d\amp=10\sqrt{10}</mrow>
                </md>The distance between <m>(6,-13)</m> and <m>(-4,17)</m> is <m>10\sqrt{10}</m> or approximately <m>31.62</m> units.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <title>The Cube Root Function</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Algebraically find the domain and graphically find the range of the function <m>g</m> where <m>g(x)=-2\sqrt[3]{x+6}-1</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>First note that the index of the function <m>g</m> for <m>g(x)=-2\sqrt[3]{x+6}-1</m> is odd. By <xref ref="fact-domain-of-radicals">Fact</xref>, the domain is <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.</p>

                <p>To find the function's range, we use technology to graph the function. According to the graph, the function's range is also <m>(-\infty,\infty)</m>.</p>
                        <figure>
                            <caption>Graph of <m>y=g(x)=-2\sqrt[3]{x+6}-1</m></caption>
                            <image width="47%">
                                <description></description>
                                <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-10,ymax=10,xmin=-15,xmax=15, ytick={-8,-6,...,8}, xtick={-12,-9,...,12}, minor xtick=, minor ytick=]
                                        \addplot[primarycurve, variable=\t, domain=-6.518:3.16, samples=50] ({(((t+1)/-2)^3-6)},{t}) node[above right, pos=0.45] {$y=-2\sqrt[3]{x+6}-1$};
                                    \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <title>Other Roots</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Algebraically find the domain and graphically find the range of the function <m>h</m> where <m>h(x)=8-\frac{5}{2}\sqrt[4]{6-2x}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>First note that the index of this function is <m>4</m>, which is even. By <xref ref="fact-domain-of-radicals">Fact</xref>, to find the domain of this function we must set the radicand greater or equal to zero and solve.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>6-2x\amp\ge0</mrow>
                        <mrow>-2x\amp\ge\subtractright{6}</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp\mathbin{\highlight{\le}}\divideunder{-6}{-2}</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp\le3</mrow>
                    </md>
                    So, the domain of <m>h</m> is <m>(-\infty,3]</m>.</p>
                    <p>To find the function's range, we use technology to graph the function. By the graph, the function's range is <m>(-\infty,8]</m>.</p>
                        <figure>
                            <caption>Graph of <m>y=h(x)=8-\frac{5}{2}\sqrt[4]{6-2x}</m></caption>
                            <image width="47%">
                                <description></description>
                                <latex-image>
                                <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                    \begin{axis}[ymin=-3,ymax=9,xmin=-10,xmax=4, ytick={-2,-1,...,8}, xtick={-8,-6,...,2}, minor xtick=, minor ytick=]
                                        \addplot[primarycurve, variable=\t, {Kite}-, domain=2.355:8] ({(((t-8)/-2.5)^4-6)/-2},{t}) node[above left, pos=0.6] {$y=8-\frac{5}{2}\sqrt[4]{6-2x}$};
                                        \addplot[soliddot, color=firstcolor] coordinates{(3,8)};
                                    \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                                </latex-image>
                            </image>
                        </figure>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Radical Expressions and Rational Exponents</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-radical-expressions-and-rational-exponents">Section</xref> we learned the <xref ref="fact-rational-exponent-rule-ii" text="title">rational exponent rule</xref> and added it to our <xref ref="list-exponent-rules-complete" text="title"> list of exponent rules</xref>.</p>

        <example>
            <title>Radical Expressions and Rational Exponents</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify the expressions using <xref ref="fact-rational-exponent-rule-i">Fact</xref> or <xref ref="fact-rational-exponent-rule-ii">Fact</xref>.
                <ol label="a." cols="4">
                    <li><p><m>100^{\sfrac{1}{2}}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>(-64)^{-\sfrac{1}{3}}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>-81^{\sfrac{3}{4}}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\left(-\frac{1}{27}\right)^{\sfrac{2}{3}}</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>100^{\sfrac{1}{2}}\amp=\left(\sqrt{100}\right)</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=10</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>(-64)^{-\sfrac{1}{3}}\amp=\frac{1}{(-64)^{\sfrac{1}{3}}}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{\left(\sqrt[3]{(-64)}\right)}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{-4}</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>-81^{\sfrac{3}{4}}\amp=-\left(\sqrt[4]{81}\right)^3</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=-3^3</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=-27</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>In this problem the negative can be associated with either the numerator or the denominator, but not both. We choose the numerator.</p>
                        <p><md>
                            <mrow>\left(-\frac{1}{27}\right)^{\sfrac{2}{3}}\amp=\left(\sqrt[3]{-\frac{1}{27}}\right)^2</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\left(\frac{\sqrt[3]{-1}}{\sqrt[3]{27}}\right)^2</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\left(\frac{-1}{3}\right)^2</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\frac{(-1)^2}{(3)^2}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\amp=\frac{1}{9}</mrow>
                        </md></p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <title>More Expressions with Rational Exponents</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Use exponent properties in <xref ref="list-exponent-rules-complete">List</xref> to simplify the expressions, and write all final versions using radicals.
                <ol label="a." cols="4">
                    <li><p><m>7z^{\sfrac{5}{9}}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\frac{5}{4}x^{-\sfrac{2}{3}}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\left(-9q^5\right)^{\sfrac{4}{5}}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\sqrt{y^5}\cdot\sqrt[4]{y^2}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\frac{\sqrt{t^3}}{\sqrt[3]{t^2}}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\sqrt{\sqrt[3]{x}}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>5\left(4+a^{\sfrac{1}{2}}\right)^2</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>-6\left(2p^{-\sfrac{5}{2}}\right)^{\sfrac{3}{5}}</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>7z^{\sfrac{5}{9}}\amp=7\sqrt[9]{z^5}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\frac{5}{4}x^{-\sfrac{2}{3}}\amp=\frac{5}{4}\cdot\frac{1}{x^{\sfrac{2}{3}}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\frac{5}{4}\cdot\frac{1}{\sqrt[3]{x^2}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\frac{5}{4\sqrt[3]{x^2}}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\left(-9q^5\right)^{\sfrac{4}{5}}\amp=\left(-9\right)^{\sfrac{4}{5}}\cdot\left(q^5\right)^{\sfrac{4}{5}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\left(-9\right)^{\sfrac{4}{5}}\cdot q^{5\cdot\sfrac{4}{5}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\left(\sqrt[5]{-9}\right)^4\cdot q^{4}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\left(q\sqrt[5]{-9}\right)^4</mrow>
                                </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\sqrt{y^5}\cdot\sqrt[4]{y^2}\amp=y^{\sfrac{5}{2}}\cdot y^{\sfrac{2}{4}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=y^{\sfrac{5}{2}+\sfrac{2}{4}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=y^{\sfrac{10}{4}+\sfrac{1}{4}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=x^{\sfrac{11}{4}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[4]{x^{11}}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\frac{\sqrt{t^3}}{\sqrt[3]{t^2}}\amp=\frac{t^{\sfrac{3}{2}}}{t^{\sfrac{2}{3}}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=t^{\sfrac{3}{2}-\sfrac{2}{3}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=t^{\sfrac{9}{6}-\sfrac{4}{6}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=t^{\sfrac{5}{6}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[6]{t^5}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\sqrt{\sqrt[3]{x}}\amp=\sqrt{x^{\sfrac{1}{3}}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\left(x^{\sfrac{1}{3}}\right)^{\sfrac{1}{2}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=x^{\sfrac{1}{3}\cdot\sfrac{1}{2}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=x^{\sfrac{1}{6}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[6]{x}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md alignment="alignat">
                                <mrow>5\left(4+a^{\sfrac{1}{2}}\right)^2\amp=5\left(4+a^{\sfrac{1}{2}}\right)\left(4+a^{\sfrac{1}{2}}\right)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=5\left(4^2+2\cdot4\cdot a^{\sfrac{1}{2}}+\left(a^{\sfrac{1}{2}}\right)^2\right)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=5\left(16+8a^{\sfrac{1}{2}}+a^{\sfrac{1}{2}\cdot 2}\right)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=5\left(16+8a^{\sfrac{1}{2}}+a\right)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=5\left(16+8\sqrt{a}+a\right)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=80+40\sqrt{a}+5a</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>-6\left(2p^{-\sfrac{5}{2}}\right)^{\sfrac{3}{5}}\amp=-6\cdot2^{\sfrac{3}{5}}\cdot p^{-\sfrac{5}{2}\cdot\sfrac{3}{5}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=-6\cdot2^{\sfrac{3}{5}}\cdot p^{-\sfrac{3}{2}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=-\frac{6\cdot 2^{\sfrac{3}{5}}}{p^{\sfrac{3}{2}}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=-\frac{6\sqrt[5]{2^3}}{\sqrt{p^3}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=-\frac{6\sqrt[5]{8}}{\sqrt{p^3}}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

   <subsection>
        <title>Radical Expression Operations</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-radical-expression-operations">Section</xref> we learned to apply properties previously learned in <xref ref="section-square-root-properties">Section</xref> to radicals with higher roots and to more complicated radical expressions. These properties include the following:

        <md>
            <mrow>\sqrt[m]{x^m}\amp=x\amp\text{where }m\text{ is odd}</mrow>
            <mrow>\sqrt[n]{x^n}\amp=\abs{x}\amp\text{where }n\text{ is even}</mrow>
            <mrow>\sqrt[n]{x\cdot y}\amp=\sqrt[n]{x}\cdot\sqrt[n]{y}</mrow>
            <mrow>\sqrt[n]{\frac{x}{y}}\amp=\frac{\sqrt[n]{x}}{\sqrt[n]{y}}, \text{ where }y\ne0</mrow>
        </md>
        </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify <m>\sqrt{y^2-4y+4}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>\sqrt{y^2-4y+4}\amp=\sqrt{(y-2)^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\abs{y-2}</mrow>
                </md>We used the property <m>\sqrt[n]{x^n}=\abs{x}\text{ where }n\text{ is even}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify <m>\sqrt[4]{48x^6y^9}</m>. Assume all variables are positive.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>\sqrt[4]{48x^6y^9}\amp=\sqrt[4]{16\cdot 3\cdot x^4\cdot x^2\cdot y^8\cdot y}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[4]{2^4\cdot 3\cdot x^4\cdot x^2\cdot \left(y^2\right)^4\cdot y}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=2xy^2\sqrt[4]{3x^2y}</mrow>
                </md>We used the property <m>\sqrt[n]{x^n}=\abs{x}\text{ where }m\text{ is even}</m>, but absolute value signs were unnecessary since all variables are assumed to be positive.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

         <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Do multiplication: <m>\sqrt[3]{4y}\cdot\sqrt[3]{10y^4}</m></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>\sqrt[3]{4y}\cdot\sqrt[3]{10y^4}\amp=\sqrt[3]{(4y)\cdot\left(10y^4\right)}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[3]{40y^5}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[3]{8\cdot 5\cdot y^3\cdot y^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[3]{2^3\cdot 5\cdot y^3\cdot y^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=2y\sqrt[3]{5y^2}</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Do division: <m>\frac{\sqrt[4]{5m^6n^{10}}}{\sqrt[4]{80m^{10}n}}</m>. Assume all variables are positive.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>\frac{\sqrt[4]{5a^5b^{12}}}{\sqrt[4]{80a^{17}b^3}}\amp=\sqrt[4]{\frac{5a^5b^{12}}{80a^{17}b^3}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[4]{\frac{1b^9}{16a^{12}}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[4]{\frac{b^8b}{2^4\left(a^3\right)^4}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{b^2\sqrt[4]{b}}{2a^3}</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>In addition, we reviewed how to add or subtract radical expressions from <xref ref="section-square-root-properties">Section</xref> and applied this concept to higher roots and more complicated radical expressions.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Simplify <m>\sqrt[3]{128x^4}-3x\sqrt[3]{54x}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><md>
                    <mrow>\sqrt[3]{128x^4}-3x\sqrt[3]{54x}\amp=\sqrt[3]{64\cdot 2\cdot x^3\cdot x}-3x\sqrt[3]{27\cdot 2\cdot x}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\sqrt[3]{4^3\cdot 2\cdot x^3\cdot x}-3x\sqrt[3]{3^3\cdot 2\cdot x}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=4x\sqrt[3]{2x}-9x\sqrt[3]{2x}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-5x\sqrt[3]{2x}</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>More on Rationalizing the Denominator</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-more-on-rationalizing-the-denominator">Section</xref> we covered how to rationalize the denominator when it contains a single square root or a binomial.</p>

        <example>
            <title>A Review of Rationalizing the Denominator</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Rationalize the denominator of the expressions.
                <ol label="a." cols="2">
                    <li><p><m>\frac{12}{\sqrt{3}}</m></p></li>
                    <li><p><m>\frac{\sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{75}}</m></p></li>
                </ol></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p><ol label="a.">
                    <li><p>
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\frac{12}{\sqrt{3}}\amp=\frac{12}{\sqrt{3}}\multiplyright{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{3}}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\frac{12\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{9}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\frac{12\sqrt{3}}{3}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=4\sqrt{3}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li><p>First we will simplify <m>\sqrt{75}</m>.
                            <md>
                                <mrow>\frac{\sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{75}}\amp=\frac{\sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{25\cdot 3}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\frac{\sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{25}\cdot\sqrt{3}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\frac{\sqrt{5}}{5\sqrt{3}}</mrow>
                                <intertext>Now we can rationalize the denominator by multiplying the numerator and denominator by <m>\sqrt{3}</m>.</intertext>
                                <mrow>\amp=\frac{\sqrt{5}}{5\sqrt{3}}\multiplyright{\frac{\sqrt{3}}{\sqrt{3}}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\frac{\sqrt{15}}{5\cdot\sqrt{9}}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\frac{\sqrt{15}}{5\cdot 3}</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=\frac{\sqrt{15}}{15}</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol></p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <title>Rationalize Denominator with Difference of Squares Formula</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Rationalize the denominator in <m>\frac{\sqrt{6}-\sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{3}+\sqrt{2}}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To remove radicals in <m>\sqrt{3}+\sqrt{2}</m> with the difference of squares formula, we multiply it with <m>\sqrt{3}-\sqrt{2}</m>.<md>
                    <mrow>\frac{\sqrt{6}-\sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{3}+\sqrt{2}}\amp=\frac{\sqrt{6}-\sqrt{5}}{\sqrt{3}+\sqrt{2}}\multiplyright{\frac{\left(\sqrt{3}-\sqrt{2}\right)}{\left(\sqrt{3}-\sqrt{2}\right)}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{\sqrt{6}\multiplyright{\sqrt{3}}-\sqrt{6}\multiplyright{\sqrt{2}}-\sqrt{5}\multiplyright{\sqrt{3}}-\sqrt{5}\multiplyright{-\sqrt{2}}}{\left(\sqrt{3}\right)^2-\left(\sqrt{2}\right)^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{\sqrt{18}-\sqrt{12}-\sqrt{15}+\sqrt{10}}{9-4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=\frac{3\sqrt{2}-2\sqrt{3}-\sqrt{15}+\sqrt{10}}{5}</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Solving Radical Equations</title>
        <p>In <xref ref="section-solving-radical-equations">Section</xref> we covered solving equations that contain a radical. We learned about extraneous solutions and the need to check our solutions.</p>

        <example>
            <title>Solving Radical Equations</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve for <m>r</m> in <m>r=9+\sqrt{r+3}</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>We will isolate the radical first, and then square both sides.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>r\amp=9+\sqrt{r+3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>r-9\amp=\sqrt{r+3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\left(r-9\right)^{\highlight{2}}\amp=\left(\sqrt{r+3}\right)^{\highlight{2}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>r^2-18r+81\amp=r+3</mrow>
                        <mrow>r^2-19r+78\amp=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>(r-6)(r-13)\amp=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>r-6=0\amp\text{ or }r-13=0</mrow>
                        <mrow>r=6\amp\text{ or }r=13</mrow>
                    </md>
                Because we squared both sides of an equation, we must check both solutions.</p>
                <p>Substitute <m>\substitute{6}</m> into <m>r=9+\sqrt{r+3}</m>, and we have:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>r\amp=9+\sqrt{r+3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\substitute{6}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}9+\sqrt{\substitute{6}+3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>6\amp\stackrel{?}{=}9+\sqrt{9}</mrow>
                        <mrow>6\amp\stackrel{?}{=}9+3</mrow>
                        <mrow>6\amp\stackrel{\text{no}}{=}12</mrow>
                    </md>
                It turns out <m>6</m> is an extraneous solution.</p>
                <p>Next, we substitute <m>\substitute{13}</m> into <m>r=9+\sqrt{r+3}</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>r\amp=9+\sqrt{r+3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\substitute{13}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}9+\sqrt{\substitute{13}+3}</mrow>
                        <mrow>13\amp\stackrel{?}{=}9+\sqrt{16}</mrow>
                        <mrow>13\amp\stackrel{?}{=}9+4</mrow>
                        <mrow>13\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}13</mrow>
                    </md>
                So, <m>13</m> is the solution.</p>
                <p>The equation has one solution: <m>13</m>. The solution set is <m>\{13\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

            <example>
                <title>Solving Radical Equations that Require Squaring Twice</title>
                <statement>
                    <p>Solve the equation <m>\sqrt{t+9}=-1-\sqrt{t}</m> for <m>t</m>.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>We cannot isolate two radicals, so we will simply square both sides, and later try to isolate the remaining radical.
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\sqrt{t+9}\amp=-1-\sqrt{t}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\left(\sqrt{t+9}\right)^\highlight{2}\amp=\left(-1-\sqrt{t}\right)^\highlight{2}</mrow>
                            <mrow>t+9\amp=1+2\sqrt{t}+t \amp\text{ after expanding the binomial squared}</mrow>
                            <mrow>9\amp=1+2\sqrt{t}</mrow>
                            <mrow>8\amp=2\sqrt{t}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\frac{8}{2}\amp=\frac{2\sqrt{t}}{2}</mrow>
                            <mrow>4\amp=\sqrt{t}</mrow>
                            <mrow>(4)^\highlight{2}\amp=\left(\sqrt{t}\right)^\highlight{2}</mrow>
                            <mrow>16\amp=t</mrow>
                        </md>
                    Because we squared both sides of an equation, we must check the solution by substituting <m>\substitute{16}</m> into <m>\sqrt{t+9}=-1-\sqrt{t}</m>, and we have:
                        <md>
                            <mrow>\sqrt{t+9}\amp=-1-\sqrt{t}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\sqrt{\substitute{16}+9}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-1-\sqrt{16}</mrow>
                            <mrow>\sqrt{25}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}-1-4</mrow>
                            <mrow>5\amp\stackrel{\text{no}}{=}-5</mrow>
                        </md>
                    Our solution did not check so there is no solution to this equation. The solution set is <m>\{\text{ }\}</m>.</p>
                </solution>
            </example>
    </subsection>

